,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":65803,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Safety Captain"},"post_url":"/t/max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue/475936/10","custom_user_title":"Safety Captain","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3460062,"name":"Ethan Leung | 2473 | Hardware Lead","username":"Ethan_L","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/ethan_l/{size}/233365_2.png","created_at":"2024-12-16T22:47:38.046Z","cooked":"<p>Just posting an update from our team here, we’ve developed our MK4n code and it works perfectly in our sim, no drift. In the same sim the MaxSwerve modules still have drift. Your code library is the same one we used and have had issues with.</p>","post_number":11,"post_type":1,"posts_count":16,"updated_at":"2024-12-16T22:47:38.046Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":69,"readers_count":68,"score":13.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":475936,"topic_slug":"max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue","display_username":"Ethan Leung | 2473 | Hardware Lead","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":59952,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue/475936/11","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3460068,"name":"joel truher","username":"truher","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/truher/{size}/172222_2.png","created_at":"2024-12-16T22:56:58.317Z","cooked":"<p>I’m curious if you’ve run something very simple, like “set every module to zero steering and 0.1 m/s velocity” … do you still see this phenomenon?</p>
<p>Note that mechanically, all the <span class="abbreviation">COTS<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Commercial, off-the-shelf"></template></span> swerve modules couple driving and steering, so if you steering “P” value is too soft, the drive force will tend to affect steering.  If all the bevels are facing the same way, you’ll see a sort of “crabbing,” and if they’re not all facing the same way, you’ll see turning.  It’s surprising how high you can make “P” without really hurting anything.  For awhile we tried to compensate for the coupling force, but it didn’t seem to help much; we just make steering “P” really high.</p>","post_number":12,"post_type":1,"posts_count":16,"updated_at":"2024-12-16T22:56:58.317Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":67,"readers_count":66,"score":13.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":475936,"topic_slug":"max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue","display_username":"joel truher","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":53190,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue/475936/12","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3460075,"name":"RockRGI","username":"RockRGI","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/rockrgi/{size}/251644_2.png","created_at":"2024-12-16T23:23:20.351Z","cooked":"<p>Check your magnets in the absolute encoders. We had this situation with the MK4i swerves and found that the locktite either failed or was not used during assembly. We learned long ago to verify mechanical before we determine it is software related. May not be your issue but literally takes a couple minutes to check it.</p>","post_number":13,"post_type":1,"posts_count":16,"updated_at":"2024-12-16T23:23:20.351Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":56,"readers_count":55,"score":11.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":475936,"topic_slug":"max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue","display_username":"RockRGI","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":27915,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue/475936/13","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3460084,"name":"","username":"TyJac42","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/tyjac42/{size}/230279_2.png","created_at":"2024-12-16T23:47:03.132Z","cooked":"<p>Has anyone successfully fixed this issue by retuning the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controller on their turning motor? Or has anyone even tried manually tuning their PIDs when using the MAX swerve template code? I have seen many people suggest this as the issue.</p>
<p>My team has seen similar symptoms on our MAX swerve and interestingly enough I have never heard this issue from someone using other swerve modules.</p>","post_number":14,"post_type":1,"posts_count":16,"updated_at":"2024-12-16T23:47:03.132Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":52,"readers_count":51,"score":10.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":475936,"topic_slug":"max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":53544,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming, CAD"},"post_url":"/t/max-swerve-turning-while-moving-forward-issue/475936/14","custom_user_title":"Programming, CAD","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3460085,"name":"Nick Foote","username":"Footie","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/footie/{size}/218325_2.png","created_at":"2024-12-16T23:57:37.500Z","cooked":"<p>Is it possible that a single swerve module has a different speed pinion set than the others, and one corner is being driven faster/slower than all the others, thus causing the turning?</p>
